         b'&raquo;</a></div>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class="post-122 post type'
         b'-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-mobile category'
         b'-recommendations category-research category-spam category-trust" id='
         b'"post-122">\n\t\t\t<h2>Redefining Information Overload</h2>\n'
         b'\n\t\t\t<div class="entry">\n\t\t\t\t<p>The other day I was sitti'
         b'ng at Gatwick airport waiting for my flight home to Italy to spend C'
         b'hristmas with my family. I got my flight with Easyjet- and when I bo'
         b'ught the ticket online I was also able to sign up to one of their ne'
         b'w, free text-messaging services:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Some of the texts '
         b'were <strong>very helpful</strong>: the morning of my flight I recei'
         b'ved a text with my flight details and confirmation number, informati'
         b'on that I may usually scribble on a piece of paper or the back of my'
         b' hand. Result: no paper, and clean hands (happier parents?)</li>'
         b'\n<li>Some of the texts could have made us of some <strong>locati'
         b'on information</strong>: a text said (in a nice way) &#8220;go to yo'
         b'ur gate&#8221; &#8230; umm, should I reply to the computer and tell '
         b'it I&#8217;m already there?</li>\n<li>Other texts were <strong>in'
         b'teresting, but I didn&#8217;t need them</strong>: &#8220;Use this te'
         b'xt to get 0% commission on currency exchange.&#8221; I have some Eur'
         b'os in my pocket. Can you send me this text again when I do need Euro'
         b's? (Maybe I&#8217;ll tell you when?)</li>\n<li>Other texts were <'
         b'strong>just useless</strong>. &#8220;Go to shop X and get Y% discoun'
         b't with this text.&#8221; I won&#8217;t say what the shop is, let&#82'
         b'17;s just leave it at the fact that its contents don&#8217;t quite f'
         b'it my profile (specifically gender). Why do you keep interupting me '
         b'from the book I was reading to give me this useless advertisement? M'
         b'y only current solution is to unsubscribe- but I&#8217;ll lose all t'
         b'he information I liked then!<span id="more-122"></span></li>\n</u'
         b'l>\n<p>To any reader of this blog, these ~4 text messages are rem'
         b'iniscent of Daniele&#8217;s work on trust models on mobile phones, a'
         b'nd I was thinking about how it overlaps with all the work on recomme'
         b'nder systems and collaborative filtering. Collaborative filtering, b'
         b'y growing out of information retrieval work, is still bound, or perh'
         b'aps tangential, to search (as was discussed at <a href="http://mobbl'
         b'og.cs.ucl.ac.uk/2007/10/23/recsys-2007/">RecSys</a>); how can we pro'
         b'vide query-less results to users based on the (possibly implicit) in'
         b'formation they provide? To that extent, there are a lot of ways it c'
         b'an spill over into the mobile world- either by using the mobile phon'
         b'e as a mere interface to centralised servers, or profiling users in '
         b'other ways, such as location, co-location, content they carry, etc ('
         b'the sort of things related to Liam&#8217;s work?). As we can see fro'
         b'm the sort of things Google is doing, people can be profiled for (ne'
         b'arly?) everything they do.</p>\n<p>However, I think that all of t'
         b'hese methods rely on two points:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>&#8220;Recommendat'
         b'ions Push:&#8221; I am looking for content. Recommender systems are '
         b'successful online because people want to explore the results they gi'
         b've. In other words, when online I am trying to pull useful recommend'
         b'ations from the system. Text messages being sent to me is not the sa'
         b'me; it is Easyjet pushing recommendations my way. I have to check my'
         b' phone and make sure its not a friend texting me.</li>\n<li>&#822'
         b'0;Recommender Trust:&#8221; I trust Easyjet to only send me the adve'
         b'rtisements they think are right for me (regardless of any accuracy c'
         b'onsiderations). In this case it feels like Easyjet is more intereste'
         b'd in sending me advertisements of shops that are in the same airport'
         b' that I should be in.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Conclusion? In the mobile wo'
         b'rld, the problem of information overload is redefined. It is no long'
         b'er &#8220;there is too much content for the user to find all that he'
         b'/she is interested in.&#8221;  My rough definition would be &#8220;i'
         b'f all the content gets pushed to all the users, their phones will ne'
         b'ver stop vibrating, they will not take any action on the content the'
         b'y receive, and they are probably going to turn their phones off.&#82'
         b'21;</p>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t<p class="postmetadata alt'
